This was based on the 3.15 PR: https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/pull/43129/files

Fixes issue dotnet/runtime#57472

Main pr dotnet/runtime#57479

Also backported to 5.0 in dotnet/runtime#57562 and 3.1 in #43102. This PR will pave the way for backporting it to the `System.Memory` OOB package for .NET Framework.

# Customer Impact

A customer has encountered dotnet/runtime#57472 while on .NET Framework and reported it in dotnet/runtime#67295, necessiating backporting it once again. As an example provided in that issue, this memory manager:

``` csharp
private sealed class BasicMemoryManager : MemoryManager<byte>
{
    private readonly byte[] _buffer;
    public BasicMemoryManager(int size = 1024) => _buffer = new byte[size];

    protected override bool TryGetArray(out ArraySegment<byte> segment)
    {
        segment = new ArraySegment<byte>(_buffer);
        return true;
    }
    public override Span<byte> GetSpan() => _buffer;

    public override MemoryHandle Pin(int elementIndex = 0) => throw new NotSupportedException();
    public override void Unpin() => throw new NotSupportedException();
    protected override void Dispose(bool disposing) { }
}
```

will fail two of the following tests:

``` csharp
[Theory]
[InlineData(0, 32)]
[InlineData(0, 29)]
[InlineData(32, 32)] // fail: length 0
[InlineData(32, 29)] // fail: length -3
public void OffsetTest(int offset, int length)
{
    var mgr = new BasicMemoryManager(1024);
    var slice = mgr.Memory.Slice(offset, length);
    Assert.Equal(length, slice.Length);

    var ros = new ReadOnlySequence<byte>(slice);
    Assert.True(ros.IsSingleSegment);
    Assert.Equal(length, ros.Length);
}
```

# Testing

Failing test has been added in this PR.

# Risk

Low, as the change is very simple and obvious when you look at `ReadOnlySequence<T>` ctor that accepts `ReadOnlyMemory<T>` (notice line 133 versus lines 140 and 148):

https://github.com/dotnet/corefx/blob/0d40b482e6b6c232131dc808182d6b32d9d37394/src/System.Memory/src/System/Buffers/ReadOnlySequence.cs#L130-L149

Moreover, the changed code gets triggered only when creating a `ReadOnlySequence` from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by a `MemoryManager`. All other use cases (including creating from an array or from a `ReadOnlyMemory` backed by an array or a string) are unaffected. And the changes are identical to those in the other backports.

# Regression

This is not a regression.

There is an unused class generated when using a method with an `Expression<Func<>` signature, e.g `Expression<Func<int>>`. Using just `Func<>` does not have this issue - in that case, the generated class is used to cache the delegate, so it seems to be a specific interaction when using expression trees.

There is no difference between Debug/Release.

**Steps to Reproduce**:

```csharp
using System;
using System.Linq.Expressions;

var t = new Test();
t.M(() => 10);

public class Test
{
    public void M(Expression<Func<int>> expression)
    {
    }
}
```

[SharpLab Link](https://sharplab.io/#v2:CYLg1APgAgTAjAWAFBQAwAIpwHQBkCWAdgI7YCiAHgA4BOApgM4P4D2hDA3MsgG4CGNdABd0AXnSE6Ad3QAVRkIAUASi5Ih2ALKKVYgHzo4qVdxQBmTDDkLkAb2TpHmC1AAs6bZVqNmbADxQAKx+REJ6BnTU9EyshMoOTvZITugAvsipQA==)

**Expected Behavior**:
No additional class is created.

**Actual Behavior**:
A class
```csharp
    [Serializable]
    [CompilerGenerated]
    private sealed class <>c
    {
        public static readonly <>c <>9 = new <>c();
    }
```
is produced, but not actually used anywhere in the code.

When a collection-expr is targeted to List (or I believe to ICollection/IList), we try to do something like the following when possible:

```cs
List<T> list = [..spread1, ..spread2, ..., ..spreadN, scalar1, scalar2, ...];

// codegen
var length = spread1.Length + spread2.Length + ... + spreadN.Length + NUM_SCALAR_ELEMENTS;
List<T> list = new();
CollectionsMarshal.SetCount(list, length);
var span = CollectionsMarshal.AsSpan(list):
((Span<T>)spread1).CopyTo(span.Slice(...));
((Span<T>)spread2).CopyTo(span.Slice(...));
...
```

However, when the spread operand is not convertible to Span, but *is* convertible to IEnumerable, we would really prefer to be able to use `list.AddRange((IEnumerable<T>)spread)`. However, this conflicts with the simplifying assumption we made by calling `SetCount` then `AsSpan` just once. We'd get bad results if we, for example, just called AddRange on the underlying list--elements would be added at the wrong position, and so on. We'd have to do some kind of interleaving of SetCount+AsSpan/AddRange/SetCount+AsSpan/... to make things work.

The impl of List.AddRange is useful as a point of reference here: https://github.com/dotnet/runtime/blob/6f30b7500ea2c0d0fb2923ea1fc5ed3c4ce2f29c/src/libraries/System.Private.CoreLib/src/System/Collections/Generic/List.cs#L243

What we would ideally do to make it straightforward to insert the spread elements is either:
1. access the underlying array of the List and pass it in to ICollection<T>.CopyTo(T[], index), as AddRange is doing internally
2. Use a runtime API under consideration to try and convert IEnumerables to ReadOnlySpan, then use CopyTo: dotnet/runtime#58821
3. Use some hypothetical new CollectionsMarshal API to, for example, create a `T[]` and move ownership of it to a new `List<T>`

Note that even if we had say, `[bunch, of, scalars, ..spread1, bunch, of, scalars]`, where `spread1` is convertible to ICollection but not Span, it might still be desirable to use `AsSpan`, as it does seem to meaningfully reduce the overhead of inserting the scalar elements into the list compared to calling `Add`. So, we wouldn't want to necessarily see a spread of an ICollection and fall back to completely using Add/AddRange instead of Span.

We removed the span temp for now per https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/pull/71195#discussion_r1425751607.

We'd like to reintroduce the span temp later, perhaps only when non-async, or when lowering can prove that the span will not be used across an await boundary, or perhaps even reinitializing the span temp when it is used across an await boundary.

This would result in a maybe 2% perf improvement for CopyTo codegen.

```cs
T[] result = [..arr1, ..arr2];

// currently becomes
((Span<T>)arr1).CopyTo((Span<T>)result).Slice(...));
((Span<T>)arr2).CopyTo((Span<T>)result).Slice(...));

// we could instead do:
Span<T> spanTemp = result;
((Span<T>)arr1).CopyTo(spanTemp.Slice(...));
((Span<T>)arr2).CopyTo(spanTemp.Slice(...));
```
